set.seed(1250)

# set 1
n = 100
mx = 0; my = 0 # mean
sx = 1; sy = 1   # standard deviation
p = 0.1   # correlation

x = rnorm(n,mx,sx)
y = sy*p*(x-mx)/sx + my + sy*rnorm(n,0,sqrt(1-p^2))
#cor.test(x,y)
df1 = data.frame(x,y)

# set 2
n = 100
mx = 2; my = 2 # mean
sx = 1; sy = 1   # standard deviation
p = 0.2   # correlation

x = rnorm(n,mx,sx)
y = sy*p*(x-mx)/sx + my + sy*rnorm(n,0,sqrt(1-p^2))
# cor.test(x,y)
df2 = data.frame(x,y)

# set 3
n = 100
mx = -2; my = 2 # mean
sx = 1; sy = 1   # standard deviation
p = 0.3   # correlation

x = rnorm(n,mx,sx)
y = sy*p*(x-mx)/sx + my + sy*rnorm(n,0,sqrt(1-p^2))
# plot(x,y)
# cor.test(x,y)
df3 = data.frame(x,y)

# Combining data sets
df4 = rbind(df2,data=df1)
df = rbind(df3,data=df4)

plot(df$x,df$y)

# without scaling 
fviz_nbclust(df, kmeans, method = "wss")+labs(title = "Clustering Without Scaling")

# K = 5   total within sum square 400

# with scale
df_scaled = scale(df)
fviz_nbclust(df_scaled, kmeans, method = "wss")+labs(title = "Clustering With scaling")

# k = 5 total within sum square 130

Without Scaling and with Scaling for both cases we can take k = 5 as optimal cluster size from elbow method

df2 = read.csv("prob1.csv")
plot(df2$X,df2$x)

df2$X = NULL

# normal likelihood
normal.lik<-function(theta,y){
  mu=theta[1]
  sigma2=theta[2]
  n=nrow(y)
  logl= -0.5*n*log(2*pi) -.5*n*log(sigma2) - (1/(2*sigma2))*sum((y-mu)**2)
  return(-logl)
}


t = c(1,3)
normal_likely = normal.lik(t,df2)
# normal likelihood estimate
normal_likely

data = read.csv("prob1.csv")

loglik = function(x,theta)
{
  return(-sum(log(theta)-theta*x))
}

library(boot)
library(ggplot2)
set.seed(155)
mle = optim(runif(1,1,200),loglik,x=data$x, method = "L-BFGS-B", lower=0.000001, upper = Inf, hessian = TRUE)
fis = solve(mle$hessian)
cat("estimated theta MLE :", mle$par)
## estimated theta MLE : 2.114092
cat("\nvariance :",fis)

## variance : 0.04469382
my.mean = function(x, indices) {
  return( mean( x[indices] ) )
}

fit = rpart(train$survived_died ~.,method="class", data=train,control =rpart.control(minsplit = 10, minbucket = 7, maxdepth = 10, usesurrogate = 2, xval =10 ))

data("College")
set.seed(2369854) 

College = dummy_cols(College,select_columns = "Private")
College$Private_No = NULL
College$Private = NULL
smp_size = floor(0.5 * nrow(College))
train_ind = sample(seq_len(nrow(College)), size = smp_size)

train = College[train_ind, ]
test = College[-train_ind, ]


# linear regression using least square method

reg = lm(train$Apps~.,data=train)
intercept = reg$coefficients[1]

pred = predict(reg,test[-1],se.fit = TRUE)
pred_reg = as.data.frame(pred$fit)
error = abs(test[1]-pred_reg$`pred$fit`)

MSE = sum(error^2)/length(pred_reg$`pred$fit`)


# Ridge regression
attach(College)

x = data.matrix(train[, c('Accept', "Enroll","Top10perc","Top25perc","F.Undergrad" ,"P.Undergrad" ,"Outstate","Room.Board","Books","Personal","PhD","Terminal","S.F.Ratio","perc.alumni","Expend","Grad.Rate","Private_Yes")])

ridge = glmnet(y=train$Apps,x=x,data=train,alpha=0)


# k fold cross validation
cv_model <- cv.glmnet(y=train$Apps,x = x ,data=train,alpha=0)

#find optimal lambda value that minimizes test MSE
best_lambda <- cv_model$lambda.min

#produce plot of test MSE by lambda value
plot(cv_model) 

best_model <- glmnet( y=train$Apps,x = x,data=train,lambda = best_lambda)

x_t = data.matrix(test[, c('Accept', "Enroll","Top10perc","Top25perc","F.Undergrad" ,"P.Undergrad" ,"Outstate","Room.Board","Books","Personal","PhD","Terminal","S.F.Ratio","perc.alumni","Expend","Grad.Rate","Private_Yes")])

y_predicted = predict(best_model, s = best_lambda, newx = x_t,data=train,lambda = best_lambda)

sst <- sum((test$Apps - mean(test$Apps))^2)
sse <- sum((y_predicted - test$Apps)^2)

avg_error = sse/length(y_predicted)

accu = 1 - (sse/sst)
# Accuracy for Ridge Regression Model
accu
## [1] 0.8845485
